```c
char *getLine(FILE *f)
{
    char *buffer = NULL;
    int buffer_size = 0, buffer_capacity = 0;

    while (1)
    {
        if (buffer_size == buffer_capacity)
        {
            buffer_capacity += 1024;
            buffer = realloc(buffer, buffer_capacity * sizeof(char));
        }

        int c = fgetc(f);

        if (c == EOF)
            break;

        if (c == '\n')
            break;

        buffer[buffer_size++] = c;
        buffer[buffer_size] = '\0';
    }

    return buffer;
}
```

This function uses dynamic memory allocation to read a line of text from the file. It starts by allocating a small buffer to store the line of text. As it reads characters from the file, it checks if the buffer is full. If it is, it allocates a new, larger buffer and copies the contents of the old buffer to the new one. This allows the function to handle lines of text that are longer than the initial buffer size. Once it has read a line of text (i.e., it has read a newline character), it returns the buffer.

